1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","1515":"1515","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1380–":"1380–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1412–1515":"1412–1515","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1412":"1412","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1405":"1405","1515":"1515","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hasant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Iran): surname denoting descent from or association with someone called   Hasan  , among the Shiite Muslims in particular from/with the son of their first imam   Ali  .","Albanian: from the Muslim personal name   Hasan   (Albanian definite form <i>Hasani</i>). This surname is common in both Albania and Kosovo; in Kosovo it is in the second half of the dozen most frequent surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Syed, Mohammad, Mohammed, Ahmad, Ali, Muhammad, Omar, Abdul, Abul, Abdullah, Anwar, Masud.","Muslim (mainly Bangladesh and India): from the Arabic personal name <i>Ḥasan</i> ‘good, handsome’. Hasan (<i>c.</i> 625–669) and his brother   Husain   were sons of the caliph ʿAlī ibn Abī Ṭālib (see   Ali  ) and, through their mother Fatima, grandsons of the prophet Muhammad. Shiite Muslims regard Hasan and his brother Husain as the true successors of Muhammad. The name is popular among Sunni Muslims as well as Shiites. See also   Hassanein  , compare   Hassan  .","Jewish: variant of   Hazan  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":75,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Hasant was born in 1380, in England as the son of Sir Hasant. He married Johanna Admonde in 1405, in Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Berkshire, England."},"et":{"1380–":"1380–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1412–1515":"1412–1515","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1412":"1412",